  "text": "Rapid sequence induction (RSI) is indicated in full--stomach patients. Pharmacological methods to prevent aspiration in full-stomach patients , including metoclopramide, antacids and H2-receptor antagonists, are currently not recommended, except in pregnant women (quality of evidence 1++; level of recommendation A) [CITATION_1] . Since the oxygen reserve in children is limited, RSI is frequently modified, with mask ventilation and pressures not exceeding 10−12 mm Hg before endotracheal intubation. Sellick's manoeuvre is not recommended because its efficacy has not been proven [CITATION_2] . Table 2 presents the indications and contraindications for inhalation induction. The anaesthetic of choice during inhalation induction is sevoflurane. It should be explained to a child how to breathe (\"like an astronaut\" or \"like a pilot\", through a mask, \"blowing\" a balloon). Induction under physical coercion should be avoided [CITATION_3] . The methods of inhalation induction are presented in Table 3 .",
